	abstract = {Dissolved oxygen in streams is frequently depressed to undesirable levels by discharges of organic waste. Oxygen levels recover through "reaeration," the absorption of atmospheric oxygen. To model streams and allocate wasteloads, the "reaeration coefficient," the absorption rate per unit oxygen deficit, is commonly estimated by predictive formulae, which this study seeks to improve.
It opens with an extensive critical assessment of work in gas transfer theory, open-channel turbulence, flow resistance, and reaeration measurement and prediction. Available formulae and field data are evaluated by an original metric which eliminates the bias of earlier techniques. It reveals distinct differences in accuracy among types of formulae, and increasing predictability with stream slope. Despite numerous formulae based on mean depth, velocity and slope, predictive errors remain very large. Some variables are clearly missing.
One of these is streambed geometry. Reaeration measurements in a laboratory channel investigated flows over four types: smooth beds; uniform, large-scale gravel roughness; "macroroughness;" and riffle-pool sequences.
Smooth-bed runs support one fundamental theory of gas transfer, based on the turbulent energy dissipation rate, which links the large scales at which energy is produced to the small ones which perform the work of overcoming interfacial resistance. Uniform flows over large-scale gravel obey the same theory but are found to require adjustments in scaling dissipation rates.
"Macroroughness elements" are large variations in bed geometry which produce locally nonuniform flow and form drag--resulting in much greater near-surface dissipation. When applied to the fundamental theory, this energy increase accounts very accurately for the observed increases in reaeration rate. Including bed particle size as a variable, a modification to the fundamental theory incorporates both uniform and macrorough flows.
Other experiments analyze the contributions of riffles and pools to reaeration--including pool expansion losses, which cannot be captured by traditional uniform-flow formulae. For this stream type, the modification includes separate hydraulic variables for pools and riffles.
Overall, the work shows that reaeration coefficients may be accurately predicted using proper estimates for the near-surface dissipation rate of turbulent energy, accounting for spatial variations in its production.},
