	abstract = {{\textless}p{\textgreater}{\textless}strong class="journal-contentHeaderColor"{\textgreater}Abstract.{\textless}/strong{\textgreater} Gas exchange is a parameter needed in stream metabolism and trace gas emissions models. One way to estimate gas exchange is via measuring the decline of added tracer gases such as sulfur hexafluoride ({\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}SF$_{\textrm{6}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater}). Estimates of oxygen ({\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}O$_{\textrm{2}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater}) gas exchange derived from {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}SF$_{\textrm{6}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater} additions require scaling via Schmidt number (\textit{Sc}) ratio, but this scaling is uncertain under conditions of high gas exchange via bubbles because scaling depends on gas solubility as well as \textit{Sc}. Because argon ({\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}Ar{\textless}/span{\textgreater}) and {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}O$_{\textrm{2}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater} have nearly identical Schmidt numbers and solubility, {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}Ar{\textless}/span{\textgreater} may be a useful tracer gas for estimating stream {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}O$_{\textrm{2}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater} exchange. Here we compared rates of gas exchange measured via {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}Ar{\textless}/span{\textgreater} and {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}SF$_{\textrm{6}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater} for turbulent mountain streams in Wyoming, USA. We measured {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}Ar{\textless}/span{\textgreater} as the ratio of {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}Ar{\textless}/span{\textgreater}\&thinsp;{\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}:{\textless}/span{\textgreater}\&thinsp;{\t