ng all streams. We suggest that {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}Ar{\textless}/span{\textgreater} is a useful tracer because it is easily measured, requires no scaling assumptions to estimate rates of {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}O$_{\textrm{2}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater} exchange, and is not an intense greenhouse gas as is {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}SF$_{\textrm{6}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater}. We caution that scaling from rates of either {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}Ar{\textless}/span{\textgreater} or {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}SF$_{\textrm{6}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater} gas exchange to {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}CO$_{\textrm{2}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater} is uncertain due to solubility effects in conditions of bubble-mediated gas transfer.{\textless}/p{\textgreater}},
