	abstract = {A number of hydraulic geometry studies have been reported since the classic work of Leopold and Maddock, and it appears that a number of misconceptions has arisen regardind the nature and magnitude of variations in the hydraulic geometry exponents between areas. To evaluate these, exponent data for 139 at-a-station sites and for 72 downstream cases were collected from the literature, and variations in the data analyzed. Histogram analysis revealed substantial differences in the exponents when considered independently, and to facilitate simultaneous comparison between the three exponents the data were plotted on tri-axial diagrams, with one axis per exponent. This was done for the at-a-station and downstream data separately. Variations within and between major climatic areas could be examined, and similarities between theoretically derived and empirically observed data appreciated. Some confusion in the literature is attributed to five basic observations. These are the fact that downstream relationships have been related to different flow levels in different studies; differences might be expected between gaging station and field data; several different methods of fitting lines to relationships have been applied; a concern has recently been expressed that simple power functions may not be the best way of empirically describing the hydraulic geometry relationships in some cases; and, finally, the debate on whether or not velocity decreases downstream at a constant flow frequency has been perpetuated and remains largely unresolved.},
